==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*brū'', from Indo-European ''*h₃bʰrū-'' ‘brow’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[brawa|brāwa]] (Dutch [[brauw]]), Old High German [[brawa|brāwa]] (German [[Braue]]), Old Norse [[brún]] (Norwegian [[brun]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[οφρῦς]], Avestan ''brvat-'', Old Church Slavonic [[бръвь]] (Russian [[бровь]]), Lithuanian [[bruve|brùve]], Old Irish [[brú]].

